By this, it a man possessed land sor ten years (or twenty, is the owner lived out os the province), the latter's action ior its recovery could, alter the lapse of that period, be defeated by a plea (called originally praescriptio, later exceptio) alleging the length oi the defendant’s possession. The rules already stated as to iusta causa and bona fides, and the positive enactments excluding certain things from this mode os acquisition, were applied here as wellas in usucapio; and there is evidence that by this new institution res mobiles could be acquired (by peregrini) as well as land. lt operated at first, as it were, as a Statute oi Limitation only, but eventually it conferred ownership, the longi· temporis possessor being allowed 'to bring a real action sor the recovery oi the object if deprived of it; see Cod. 7. 39 8. pr.

When Justinian became emperor, the law oi Prescription in his dominions consisted- really of two heterogeneous portions. Res mobiles could be acquired by the old civil law usucapio in a year ; but prac- tically all the soil os the Eastern Empire was ‘provincial' so that the old biennii usucapio had no application; its place was supplied by the praetorian longi temporis possessio oi ten or twenty years.
